 {

  "response_text": "At the outset of the simulation, no households exhibit active social learning engagement. During the initial seven time steps, the number of households participating in social learning increases sharply, indicating a rapid initial diffusion of social learning behaviors. This growth continues through approximately time step 40, though at progressively decelerating rates, suggesting the system is approaching a saturation point as the pool of potential adopters diminishes.\n\nThe population of social learners reaches a maximum of approximately 32 households around time step 63 and maintains roughly this level through time step 100, ending at approximately 32 households. Given that the model initializes with only 20 households of the dedicated E-RO-SL1 type, the sustained level of approximately 32 participants indicates that roughly 12 additional households—drawn from the baseline E-RO or learning-by-doing E-LBD populations—have adopted social learning strategies over the course of the simulation. This represents the diffusion of social learning capabilities beyond the initially designated agents to encompass roughly 53 percent of the total household population.\n\nThe trajectory exhibits oscillatory dynamics superimposed on the overall increasing trend, with notable fluctuations occurring between time steps 22–32 and again around time steps 51–59. These variations suggest temporary reversals or heterogeneous timing in strategy adoption across the heterogeneous agent population. A marked shift in the system's dynamics occurs around time step 40, after which the rate of increase in social learning participation slows considerably, consistent with a logistic adoption pattern where the majority of behavioral switching occurs during the first half of the simulation period."
}

